description.narrative:
With the Kenyan prisons system at more than 200% capacity, a crisis in congestion is inevitable unless measures are taken to reduce the number of untried suspects remanded in custody, review current sentencing policy and practice, including to increase the use of non-custodial sentences, and develop a conditional release system that will allow those prisoners who can safely do so to complete their sentences in the community.  The acute overcrowding serves to exacerbate problems such as hygiene, santitation, privacy, health care, inte-prisoner violence, restrictions on contact with the outside world and incidents of cruel, inhuman and degrading treatment of prisoners by authorities.  It also promotes recidivism as well as hampers the social integration of prisoners. Prison staff also face serious challenges, including inadequate training, unsafe working conditions and very poor living conditions. 

The proposed programme of the Swedish Prison and Probation Service (SPPS) aims at contributing to constructive solutions of these serious problems of the Kenyan prisons system. SPPS will work closely with the Kenyan Prison Service (KPS) and the Kenyan Probation and Aftervare Service (KPAS) on day-to- day rules, regulations, routines, methods and behaviour. 

The two programme objectives are:
- improved capacity at KPS to use a needs-based approach in the rehabilitation of prisoners in a secure and humane environment and;
- improved capacity at KPAS to develop a more efficient and professional alternative supervised sanction in Kenya.

More specifically, these objectives will be achieved through:
- enhancing staff capacity of KPS  through improved methods and tools for secure, humane rehabilitation and social integration of offenders;
- enhancing professional competencies among KPAS staff.
- enhancing management capacity of both KPS and KPAS;
- improving quality of offender assessment and information management (KPS and KPAS);
- improving capacity among staff in Youth Correctional Centers and Penal Facilities for Special Needs Offenders;
- strengthening communication and cooperation within KPS and KPAS, between the two, and between them and other stakeholders in the justice system.

SPPS proposes a three-year programme 1 July 2015 - 30 June 2018 and a total budget of 32 million SEK. The programme will be a joint undertaking by SPPS, KPS and KPAS under the leadership of a Programme Management Team (PMT) consisting of two Kenyan National Programme Managers, two Swedish Correction Advisors and one coordinating Swedish Project Manager. SPPS will also provide the programme with experts and trainers in all relevant areas. Sida will be the sole funder of the programme. The programme will be interlinked with the recently started Kenya Programme of the Raoul Wallenberg Institute, supported by Sida for the period 2015-2017. The two programmes will have a joint Programme Steering Committee.
